# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: open-graph-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] The **`<meta>`** HTML element represents metadata that cannot be represented by other meta-related elements, such as `<base>`, `<link>`, `<script>`, `<style>`, or `<title>`.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] This attribute declares the document's character encoding.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] If the attribute is present, its value must be an ASCII case-insensitive match for the string `"utf-8"`, because UTF-8 is the only valid encoding for HTML5 documents.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] `<meta>` elements which declare a character encoding must be located entirely within the first 1024 bytes of the document.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] This attribute contains the value for the `http-equiv` or `name` attribute, depending on which is used.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] Defines a pragma directive, which are instructions for the browser for processing the document.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] The attribute's name is short for `http-equivalent` because the allowed values are names of equivalent HTTP headers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] The `media` attribute defines which media the theme color defined in the `content` attribute should be applied to.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] Its value is a media query, which defaults to `all` if the attribute is missing.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] This attribute is only relevant when the element's `name` attribute is set to `theme-color`.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] Otherwise, it has no effect, and should not be included.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] The `name` and `content` attributes can be used together to provide document metadata in terms of name-value pairs, with the `name` attribute giving the metadata name, and the `content` attribute giving the value.
[src:open-graph-protocol/element-meta] The following example uses `http-equiv="refresh"` to direct the browser to perform a redirect.
[src:open-graph-protocol/elements-head] The **`<head>`** HTML element contains machine-readable information (metadata) about the document, like its title, scripts, and style sheets.
[src:open-graph-protocol/elements-head] There can be only one `<head>` element in an HTML document.
[src:open-graph-protocol/elements-head] The URIs of one or more metadata profiles, separated by white space.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The **Facebook Platform** is the set of services, tools, and products provided by the social networking service Facebook for third-party developers to create their own applications and services that access data in Facebook.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The current Facebook Platform was launched in 2010.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The platform offers a set of programming interfaces and tools which enable developers to integrate with the open "social graph" of personal relations and other things like songs, places, and Facebook pages.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Applications on facebook.com, external websites, and devices are all allowed to access the graph.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook launched the Facebook Platform on May 24, 2007, providing a framework for software developers to create applications that interact with core Facebook features.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] A markup language called Facebook Markup Language was introduced simultaneously; it is used to customize the "look and feel" of applications that developers create.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The Facebook Platform made it possible for outside partners to build similar applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Many of the popular early social network games would combine capabilities.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] For instance, one of the early games to reach the top application spot, (Lil) Green Patch, combined virtual Gifts with Event notifications to friends and contributions to charities through Causes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Third-party companies provide application metrics, and several blogs arose in response to the clamor for Facebook applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] On July 4, 2007, Altura Ventures announced the "Altura 1 Facebook Investment Fund," becoming the world's first Facebook-only venture capital firm.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Tech blog Valleywag has criticized Facebook Applications, labeling them a "cornucopia of uselessness." Others have called for limiting third-party applications so the Facebook user experience is not degraded.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Applications that have been created on the Platform include chess, which both allow users to play games with their friends.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] In such games, a user's moves are saved on the website, allowing the next move to be made at any time rather than immediately after the previous move.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] By November 3, 2007, seven thousand applications had been developed on the Facebook Platform, with another hundred created every day.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] By the second annual f8 developers conference on July 23, 2008, the number of applications had grown to 33,000, and the number of registered developers had exceeded 400,000.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Within a few months of launching the Facebook Platform, issues arose regarding "application spam", which involves Facebook applications "spamming" users to request it be installed.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook integration was announced for the Xbox 360 and Nintendo DSi on June 1, 2009 at E3.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] On November 18, 2009, Sony announced an integration with Facebook to deliver the first phase of a variety of new features to further connect and enhance the online social experiences of PlayStation 3.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] On February 2, 2010, Facebook announced the release of *HipHop for PHP* as an opensource project.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Mark Zuckerberg said that his team from Facebook is developing a Facebook search engine. “Facebook is pretty well placed to respond to people’s questions.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] We have a team that is working on it", said Mark Zuckerberg.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] On June 10, 2014, Facebook announced Haxl, a Haskell library that simplified the access to remote data, such as databases or web-based services.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Starting in 2007, Facebook formed data sharing partnerships with at least 60 handset manufacturers, including Apple, Amazon, BlackBerry, Microsoft and Samsung.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Those manufacturers were provided with Facebook user data without the users' consent.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Most of the partnerships remained in place as of 2018, when the partnerships were first publicly reported.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The Graph API is the core of Facebook Platform, enabling developers to read from and write data into Facebook.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The Graph API presents a simple, consistent view of the Facebook social graph, uniformly representing objects in the graph (e.g., people, photos, events, and pages) and the connections between them (e.g., friend relationships, shared content, and photo tags).
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] On April 30, 2015, Facebook shut down friends' data API prior to the v2.0 release.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook authentication enables developers’ applications to interact with the Graph API on behalf of Facebook users, and it provides a single-sign on mechanism across web, mobile, and desktop apps.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook Connect, also called Log in with Facebook, like OpenID, is a set of authentication APIs from Facebook that developers can use to help their users connect and share with such users' Facebook friends (on and off Facebook) and increase engagement for their website or application.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] When so used, Facebook members can log on to third-party websites, applications, mobile devices and gaming systems with their Facebook identity and, while logged in, can connect with friends via these media and post information and updates to their Facebook profile.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Originally unveiled during Facebook's developer conference, F8, in July 2008, Log in with Facebook became generally available in December 2008.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] According to an article from The New York Times, "Some say the services are representative of surprising new thinking in Silicon Valley.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Log in with Facebook cannot be used by users in locations that cannot access Facebook, even if the third-party site is otherwise accessible from that location.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] According to Facebook, users who logged into *The Huffington Post* with Facebook spent more time on the site than the average user.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Social plugins – including the Like Button, Recommendations, and Activity Feed – enable developers to provide social experiences to their users with just a few lines of HTML.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] All social plugins are extensions of Facebook and are designed so that no user data is shared with the sites on which they appear.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] On the other hand, the social plugins let Facebook track its users’ browsing habits through any sites that feature the plugins.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The Open Graph protocol enables developers to integrate their pages into Facebook's global mapping/tracking tool Social Graph.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] These pages gain the functionality of other graph objects including profile links and stream updates for connected users.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook uses iframes to allow third-party developers to create applications that are hosted separately from Facebook, but operate within a Facebook session and are accessed through a user's profile.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Since iframes essentially nest independent websites within a Facebook session, their content is distinct from Facebook formatting.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook originally used 'Facebook Markup Language (FBML)' to allow Facebook Application developers to customize the "look and feel" of their applications, to a limited extent.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] FBML is a specification of how to encode content so that Facebook's servers can read and publish it, which is needed in the Facebook-specific feed so that Facebook's system can properly parse content and publish it as specified.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] FBML set by any application is cached by Facebook until a subsequent API call replaces it.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook also offers a specialized Facebook JavaScript (FBJS) library.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook stopped accepting new FBML applications on March 18, 2011, but continued to support existing FBML tabs and applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Since January 1, 2012 FBML was no longer supported, and FBML no longer functioned as of June 1, 2012.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] In February 2011, Facebook began to use the hCalendar microformat to mark up events, and the hCard for the events' venues, enabling the extraction of details to users' own calendar or mapping applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The UI framework for the mobile website is based on Xhp, the Javelin JavaScript library, and WURFL.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] The mobile platform has grown dramatically in popularity since its launch.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] In December 2012, the number of users signing into the site from mobile devices exceeded web-based logins for the first time.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Many Facebook application developers have attempted to create viral applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Stanford University even offered a class in the Fall of 2007, entitled Computer Science (CS) 377W: "Create Engaging Web Applications Using Metrics and Learning on Facebook".
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Numerous applications created by the class were highly successful, and ranked amongst the top Facebook applications, with some achieving over 3.5 million users in a month.
[src:open-graph-protocol/facebook-platform] Facebook Platform is relatively unknown to the general public, with no notable occurrences relating to it, as the privacy policy and terms and conditions are regularly updated.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The meta element has two uses: either to emulate the use of an HTTP response header field, or to embed additional metadata within the HTML document.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] With HTML up to and including HTML 4.01 and XHTML, there were four valid attributes: `content`, `http-equiv`, `name` and `scheme`.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Under HTML 5, `charset` has been added and `scheme` has been removed.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] `http-equiv` is used to emulate an HTTP header, and `name` to embed metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The value of the statement, in either case, is contained in the `content` attribute, which is the only required attribute unless `charset` is given.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] `charset` is used to indicate the character set of the document, and is available in HTML5.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Such elements must be placed as tags in the `head` section of an HTML or XHTML document.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] `meta` elements can specify HTTP headers which should be sent before the actual content when the HTML page is served from the web server to the client.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] as an alternative to the response header `Content-Type:` to indicate the media type and, more commonly needed, the UTF-8 character encoding.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] In this example, the `meta` element describes the contents of a web page.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Meta elements provide information about the web page, which can be used by search engines to help categorize the page correctly.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] They have been the focus of a field of marketing research known as search engine optimization (SEO), where different methods are used to provide a user's website with a higher ranking on search engines.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Prior to the rise of content-analysis by search engines in the mid-1990s (most notably Google), search engines were reliant on metadata to correctly classify a Web page and webmasters quickly learned the commercial significance of having the right meta element.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The search engine community is now divided as to the value of meta tags.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Some claim they have no value, others that they are central, while many simply conclude there is no clear answer but, since they do no harm, they use them just in case.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google states they do support the meta tags "description", "robots", "google", "google-site-verification", "content-type", "refresh" and "google-bot".
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Major search engine robots look at many factors when determining how to rank a page of which meta tags will only form a portion.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Furthermore, most search engines change their ranking rules frequently.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google have stated they update their ranking rules every 48 hours.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Under such circumstances, a definitive understanding of the role of meta tags in SEO is unlikely.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The `keywords` attribute was popularized by search engines such as Infoseek and AltaVista in 1995, and its popularity quickly grew until it became one of the most commonly used `meta` elements.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] No consensus exists whether or not the `keywords` attribute has any effect on ranking at any of the major search engines today.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] It is speculated that it does if the keywords used in the `meta` can also be found in the page copy itself.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] However, both these articles suggest that Yahoo! still makes use of the keywords meta tag in some of its rankings.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Yahoo! itself claims support for the keywords meta tag in conjunction with other factors for improving search rankings.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] In October 2009 Search Engine Round Table announced that "Yahoo Drops The Meta Keywords Tag Also" but later reported that the announcement made by Yahoo!'s Senior Director of Search was incorrect.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google said that this may help worthy content to get noticed.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The syntax of the news meta keyword has subtle difference from custom keyword meta tag; it is denoted by "news_keywords", while the custom keyword meta tag is denoted by "keywords".
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google News no longer takes into account keywords announced by news_keywords.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] According to Moz, "Title tags are the second most important on-page factor for SEO, after content".
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] They convey to the search engines what a given page is all about.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] It used to be standard SEO practice to include the primary and the secondary keywords in the title for better ranking.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google has gone through various iterations of showing short or longer amounts of content from within the title tags.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Regardless, the title tags still hold importance in three different ways.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The `robots` attribute, supported by several major search engines, controls whether search engine spiders are allowed to index a page, or not, and whether they should follow links from a page, or not.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The attribute can contain one or more comma-separate values.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The `noindex` value prevents a page from being indexed, and `nofollow` prevents links from being crawled.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Other values recognized by one or more search engines can influence how the engine indexes pages, and how those pages appear on the search results.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] These include `noarchive`, which instructs a search engine not to store an archived copy of the page, and `nosnippet`, which asks that the search engine not include a snippet from the page along with the page's listing in search results.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Meta tags are one of the best options for preventing search engines from indexing content of a website.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The search engines Google, Yahoo! and MSN used in some cases the title and abstract of the DMOZ (aka Open Directory Project) listing of a website for the title and/or description (also called snippet or abstract) in the search engine results pages (SERP).
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] To give webmasters the option to specify that the Open Directory Project content should not be used for listings of their website, Microsoft introduced in May 2006 the new "`NOODP`" value for the "`robots`" element of the meta tags.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google followed in July 2006 and Yahoo! in October 2006.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] By 2017, Google reported stopping the use of DMOZ, following its closure, hence, NOODP directive is ignored since.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The syntax is the same for all search engines who support the tag.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Yahoo! puts content from their own Yahoo! directory next to the ODP listing.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] In 2007 they introduced a meta tag that lets web designers opt-out of this.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Adding the `NOYDIR` tag to a page will prevent Yahoo! from displaying Yahoo!
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google does not use HTML keyword or meta tag elements for indexing.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The Director of Research at Google, Monika Henzinger, was quoted (in 2002) as saying, "Currently we don't trust metadata because we are afraid of being manipulated." Other search engines developed techniques to penalize Web sites considered to be "cheating the system".
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] For example, a Web site repeating the same meta keyword several times may have its ranking *decreased* by a search engine trying to eliminate this practice, though that is unlikely.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] It is more likely that a search engine will ignore the meta keyword element completely, and most do regardless of how many words are used in the element.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Google does, however, use meta tag elements for displaying site links.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Additionally, enterprise search startup Swiftype considers meta tags as a mechanism for signaling relevancy for their web site search engines, even introducing their own extension called Meta Tags 2.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Meta refresh elements can be used to instruct a Web browser to automatically refresh a Web page after a given time interval.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] It is also possible to specify an alternative URL and use this technique in order to redirect the user to a different location.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Auto refreshing via a META element has been deprecated for more than ten years, and recognized as problematic before that.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The W3C suggests that user agents should allow users to disable it, otherwise META refresh should not be used by web pages.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] For Internet Explorer's security settings, under the miscellaneous category, meta refresh can be turned off by the user, thereby disabling its redirect ability.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] In Mozilla Firefox it can be disabled in the configuration file under the key name "accessibility.blockautorefresh".
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Many web design tutorials also point out that client-side redirecting tends to interfere with the normal functioning of a Web browser's "back" button.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] After being redirected, clicking the back button will cause the user to go back to the redirect page, which redirects them again.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Some modern browsers seem to overcome this problem however, including Safari, Mozilla Firefox and Opera.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Auto-redirects via markup (versus server-side redirects) are not in compliance with the W3C's – Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 1.0 (guideline 7.5).
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Meta elements of the form `<meta http-equiv="foo" content="bar">` can be used as alternatives to HTTP headers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] For example, `<meta http-equiv="expires" content="Wed, 21 June 2006 14:25:27 GMT">` would tell the browser that the page "expires" on June 21, 2006 at 14:25:27 GMT and that it may safely cache the page until then.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] The HTML 4.01 specification optionally allows this tag to be parsed by HTTP servers and set as part of the HTTP response headers, but no web servers currently implement this behavior.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Instead, the user agent emulates the behavior for some HTTP headers as if they had been sent in the response header itself.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] Some HTML elements and attributes already handle certain pieces of meta data and may be used by authors instead of META to specify those pieces: the TITLE element, the ADDRESS element, the INS and DEL elements, the title attribute, and the cite attribute.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] An alternative to `meta` elements for enhanced subject access within a website is the use of a back-of-book-style index for the website.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] See the American Society of Indexers website for an example.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] In 1994, ALIWEB, also used an index file to provide the type of information commonly found in meta keywords attributes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] In cases where the content attribute's value is a URL, many authors decide to use a link element with a proper value for its rel attribute as well.
[src:open-graph-protocol/meta-element] For a comparison on when it is best to use HTTP-headers, meta-elements, or attributes in the case of language specification: see here.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] As such, efforts to define, classify types, or structure metadata are expressed as examples in the context of its use.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" has a history dating to the 1960s where it occurred in computer science and in popular culture.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Different types of metadata serve different functions.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, descriptive metadata for a document might include the author, creation date, file size and keywords.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] It can help users find relevant information and discover resources.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] It can also help organize electronic resources, provide digital identification, and archive and preserve resources.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata allows users to access resources by "allowing resources to be found by relevant criteria, identifying resources, bringing similar resources together, distinguishing dissimilar resources, and giving location information".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata of telecommunication activities including Internet traffic is very widely collected by various national governmental organizations.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This data is used for the purposes of traffic analysis and can be used for mass surveillance.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Unique metadata standards exist for different disciplines (e.g., museum collections, digital audio files, websites, etc.).
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Describing the contents and context of data or data files increases its usefulness.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, a web page may include metadata specifying what software language the page is written in (e.g., HTML), what tools were used to create it, what subjects the page is about, and where to find more information about the subject.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This metadata can automatically improve the reader's experience and make it easier for users to find the web page online.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A CD may include metadata providing information about the musicians, singers, and songwriters whose work appears on the disc.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] In many countries, government organizations routinely store metadata about emails, telephone calls, web pages, video traffic, IP connections, and cell phone locations.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata is not strictly bound to one of these categories, as it can describe a piece of data in many other ways.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] While the metadata application is manifold, covering a large variety of fields, there are specialized and well-accepted models to specify types of metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Bretherton & Singley (1994) distinguish between two distinct classes: structural/control metadata and guide metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes the structure of database objects such as tables, columns, keys and indexes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] *Guide metadata* helps humans find specific items and is usually expressed as a set of keywords in a natural language.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] According to Ralph Kimball, metadata can be divided into three categories: *technical metadata* (or internal metadata), *business metadata* (or external metadata), and *process metadata*.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Business metadata is important because it can greatly facilitate the usefulness of the data to business people.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A simple example of business metadata is a glossary entry.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Hover functionality in an application or web form can enable a glossary definition to be shown when cursor is on a field or term.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Other examples of business metadata include annotation ability within applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, a business user may be viewing a business intelligence (BI) report and notice a trend in the data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The user may have background knowledge as to why this trend occurs.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Some business intelligence tools enable the user to create an annotation within the report that explains the trend.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Such an annotation can enhance other users' understanding of the data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This example is especially powerful because it is created by a business user for the use of other business people.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] NISO distinguishes three types of metadata: descriptive, structural, and administrative.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] *Descriptive metadata* is typically used for discovery and identification, as information to search and locate an object, such as title, authors, subjects, keywords, and publisher.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes how the components of an object are organized.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] An example of structural metadata would be how pages are ordered to form chapters of a book.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Finally, *administrative metadata* gives information to help manage the source.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Administrative metadata refers to the technical information, such as file type, or when and how the file was created.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Two sub-types of administrative metadata are rights management metadata and preservation metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] *Rights management metadata* explains intellectual property rights, while *preservation metadata* contains information to preserve and save a resource.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] An additional type of metadata beginning to be more developed is *accessibility metadata*.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Accessibility metadata is not a new concept to libraries; however, advances in universal design have raised its profile.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Projects like Cloud4All and GPII identified the lack of common terminologies and models to describe the needs and preferences of users and information that fits those needs as a major gap in providing universal access solutions.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Those types of information are accessibility metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The Schema.org website has incorporated several accessibility properties based on IMS Global Access for All Information Model Data Element Specification.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] While the efforts to describe and standardize the varied accessibility needs of information seekers are beginning to become more robust, their adoption into established metadata schemas has not been as developed.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, while Dublin Core (DC)'s "audience" and MARC 21's "reading level" could be used to identify resources suitable for users with dyslexia and DC's "format" could be used to identify resources available in braille, audio, or large print formats, there is more work to be done.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata was traditionally used in the card catalogs of libraries until the 1980s when libraries converted their catalog data to digital databases.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] In the 2000s, as data and information were increasingly stored digitally, this digital data was described using metadata standards.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] An early description of "meta data" for computer systems was written by David Griffel and Stuart McIntosh at the MIT Center for International Studies in 1967: "In summary then, we have statements in an object language about subject descriptions of data and token codes for the data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata is defined as the data providing information about one or more aspects of the data; it is used to summarize basic information about data that can make tracking and working with specific data easier.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, a digital image may include metadata that describes the size of the image, its color depth, resolution, when it was created, the shutter speed, and other data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A text document's metadata may contain information about how long the document is, who the author is, when the document was written, and a short summary of the document.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata within web pages can also contain descriptions of page content, as well as key words linked to the content.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] These links are often called "Metatags", which were used as the primary factor in determining order for a web search until the late 1990s.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The reliance on metatags in web searches was decreased in the late 1990s because of "keyword stuffing", whereby metatags were being largely misused to trick search engines into thinking some websites had more relevance in the search than they really did.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata can be stored and managed in a database, often called a metadata registry or metadata repository.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] However, without context and a point of reference, it might be impossible to identify metadata just by looking at it.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example: by itself, a database containing several numbers, all 13 digits long could be the results of calculations or a list of numbers to plug into an equation – without any other context, the numbers themselves can be perceived as the data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] But if given the context that this database is a log of a book collection, those 13-digit numbers may now be identified as ISBNs – information that refers to the book, but is not itself the information within the book.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" was coined in 1968 by Philip Bagley, in his book "Extension of Programming Language Concepts" where it is clear that he uses the term in the ISO 11179 "traditional" sense, which is "structural metadata" i.e.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] "data about the containers of data"; rather than the alternative sense "content about individual instances of data content" or metacontent, the type of data usually found in library catalogs.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Since then the fields of information management, information science, information technology, librarianship, and GIS have widely adopted the term.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] In these fields, the word *metadata* is defined as "data about data".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] While this is the generally accepted definition, various disciplines have adopted their own more specific explanations and uses of the term.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) or, more correctly, the vocabularies used to assemble metadata (metacontent) statements, is typically structured according to a standardized concept using a well-defined metadata scheme, including metadata standards and metadata models.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Tools such as controlled vocabularies, taxonomies, thesauri, data dictionaries, and metadata registries can be used to apply further standardization to the metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Structural metadata commonality is also of paramount importance in data model development and in database design.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) syntax refers to the rules created to structure the fields or elements of metadata (metacontent).
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A single metadata scheme may be expressed in a number of different markup or programming languages, each of which requires a different syntax.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, Dublin Core may be expressed in plain text, HTML, XML, and RDF.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A common example of (guide) metacontent is the bibliographic classification, the subject, the Dewey Decimal class number.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] There is always an implied statement in any "classification" of some object.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] To classify an object as, for example, Dewey class number 514 (Topology) (i.e. books having the number 514 on their spine) the implied statement is: "<book><subject heading><514>".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This is a subject-predicate-object triple, or more importantly, a class-attribute-value triple.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The first 2 elements of the triple (class, attribute) are pieces of some structural metadata having a defined semantic.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The third element is a value, preferably from some controlled vocabulary, some reference (master) data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The combination of the metadata and master data elements results in a statement which is a metacontent statement i.e.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] All of these elements can be thought of as "vocabulary".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Both metadata and master data are vocabularies that can be assembled into metacontent statements.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] There are many sources of these vocabularies, both meta and master data: UML, EDIFACT, XSD, Dewey/UDC/LoC, SKOS, ISO-25964, Pantone, Linnaean Binomial Nomenclature, etc.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The process indexes pages and then matches text strings using its complex algorithm; there is no intelligence or "inferencing" occurring, just the illusion thereof.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can be hierarchical in nature where relationships exist between metadata elements and elements are nested so that parent-child relationships exist between the elements.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] An example of a hierarchical metadata schema is the IEEE LOM schema, in which metadata elements may belong to a parent metadata element.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can also be one-dimensional, or linear, where each element is completely discrete from other elements and classified according to one dimension only.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] An example of a linear metadata schema is the Dublin Core schema, which is one-dimensional.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata are often 2 dimensional, or planar, where each element is completely discrete from other elements but classified according to 2 orthogonal dimensions.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The degree to which the data or metadata is structured is referred to as "granularity".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] "Granularity" refers to how much detail is provided.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata with a high granularity allows for deeper, more detailed, and more structured information and enables a greater level of technical manipulation.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A lower level of granularity means that metadata can be created for considerably lower costs but will not provide as detailed information.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The major impact of granularity is not only on creation and capture, but moreover on maintenance costs.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] As soon as the metadata structures become outdated, so too is the access to the referred data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Hence granularity must take into account the effort to create the metadata as well as the effort to maintain it.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] In all cases where the metadata schemata exceed the planar depiction, some type of hypermapping is required to enable display and view of metadata according to chosen aspect and to serve special views.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Hypermapping frequently applies to layering of geographical and geological information overlays.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] International standards apply to metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Much work is being accomplished in the national and international standards communities, especially ANSI (American National Standards Institute) and ISO (International Organization for Standardization) to reach a consensus on standardizing metadata and registries.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The core metadata registry standard is ISO/IEC 11179 Metadata Registries (MDR), the framework for the standard is described in ISO/IEC 11179-1:2004.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] A new edition of Part 1 is in its final stage for publication in 2015 or early 2016.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] It has been revised to align with the current edition of Part 3, ISO/IEC 11179-3:2013 which extends the MDR to support the registration of Concept Systems.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This standard specifies a schema for recording both the meaning and technical structure of the data for unambiguous usage by humans and computers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 standard refers to metadata as information objects about data, or "data about data".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] In ISO/IEC 11179 Part-3, the information objects are data about Data Elements, Value Domains, and other reusable semantic and representational information objects that describe the meaning and technical details of a data item.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This standard also prescribes the details for a metadata registry, and for registering and administering the information objects within a Metadata Registry.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 Part 3 also has provisions for describing compound structures that are derivations of other data elements, for example through calculations, collections of one or more data elements, or other forms of derived data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This standard has become the general basis for other kinds of metadata registries, reusing and extending the registration and administration portion of the standard.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The Geospatial community has a tradition of specialized geospatial metadata standards, particularly building on traditions of map- and image-libraries and catalogs.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Formal metadata is usually essential for geospatial data, as common text-processing approaches are not applicable.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The Dublin Core metadata terms are a set of vocabulary terms that can be used to describe resources for the purposes of discovery.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The W3C Data Catalog Vocabulary (DCAT) is an RDF vocabulary that supplements Dublin Core with classes for Dataset, Data Service, Catalog, and Catalog Record.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] DCAT also uses elements from FOAF, PROV-O, and OWL-Time.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] DCAT provides an RDF model to support the typical structure of a catalog that contains records, each describing a dataset or service.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Although not a standard, Microformat (also mentioned in the section metadata on the internet below) is a web-based approach to semantic markup which seeks to re-use existing HTML/XHTML tags to convey metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Microformat follows XHTML and HTML standards but is not a standard in itself.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] In metadata, Naming and Design Rules are a set of guidelines and naming conventions that go beyond what a single data exchange standard specification will permit.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] The most common standard that Naming and Design Rules are created on is XML Schema.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] For example, the use of upper camel case data element names is a convention used in many standard but is not specified by the XML Schema specification.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Naming and Design Rules have become an important aspect of each organizations data exchange standards.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Within the United States, Naming and Design Rules standards are recommended for each federal and state agency.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Most common types of computer files can embed metadata, including documents, (e.g.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Microsoft Office files, OpenDocument files, PDF) images, (e.g.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata may be added to files by users, but some metadata is often automatically added to files by authoring applications or by devices used to produce the files, without user intervention.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] While metadata in files are useful for finding them, they can be a privacy hazard when the files are shared.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Using metadata removal tools to clean files before sharing them can mitigate this risk.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Some metadata is created by the camera such as, color space, color channels, exposure time, and aperture (EXIF), while some is input by the photographer and/or software after downloading to a computer.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Most digital cameras write metadata about the model number, shutter speed, etc., and some enable you to edit it; this functionality has been available on most Nikon DSLRs since the Nikon D3, on most new Canon cameras since the Canon EOS 7D, and on most Pentax DSLRs since the Pentax K-3.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata can be used to make organizing in post-production easier with the use of key-wording.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Filters can be used to analyze a specific set of photographs and create selections on criteria like rating or capture time.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] On devices with geolocation capabilities like GPS (smartphones in particular), the location the photo was taken from may also be included.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Photographic Metadata Standards are governed by organizations that develop the following standards.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata is particularly useful in video, where information about its contents (such as transcripts of conversations and text descriptions of its scenes) is not directly understandable by a computer, but where an efficient search of the content is desirable.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] This is particularly useful in video applications such as Automatic Number Plate Recognition and Vehicle Recognition Identification software, wherein license plate data is saved and used to create reports and alerts.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Avid's MetaSync and Adobe's Bridge are examples of professional video editing software with access to metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Various file systems are utilising metadata, such as FAT32 and NTFS.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Information on the times, origins and destinations of phone calls, electronic messages, instant messages, and other modes of telecommunication, as opposed to message content, is another form of metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Geospatial metadata relates to Geographic Information Systems (GIS) files, maps, images, and other data that is location-based.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] Metadata is used in GIS to document the characteristics and attributes of geographic data, such as database files and data that is developed within a GIS.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p01] It includes details like who developed the data, when it was collected, how it was processed, and what formats it's available in, and then delivers the context for the data to be used effectively.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata can be created either by automated information processing or by manual work.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Elementary metadata captured by computers can include information about when an object was created, who created it, when it was last updated, file size, and file extension.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] A metadata engine collects, stores and analyzes information about data and metadata in use within a domain.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Data virtualization emerged in the 2000s as the new software technology to complete the virtualization "stack" in the enterprise.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata is used in data virtualization servers which are enterprise infrastructure components, alongside database and application servers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata in these servers is saved as persistent repository and describe business objects in various enterprise systems and applications.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Structural metadata commonality is also important to support data virtualization.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Standardization and harmonization work has brought advantages to industry efforts to build metadata systems in the statistical community.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Several metadata guidelines and standards such as the European Statistics Code of Practice and ISO 17369:2013 (Statistical Data and Metadata Exchange or SDMX) provide key principles for how businesses, government bodies, and other entities should manage statistical data and metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Entities such as Eurostat, European System of Central Banks, and the U.S.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Environmental Protection Agency have implemented these and other such standards and guidelines with the goal of improving "efficiency when managing statistical business processes".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata has been used in various ways as a means of cataloging items in libraries in both digital and analog formats.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Such data helps classify, aggregate, identify, and locate a particular book, DVD, magazine, or any object a library might hold in its collection.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Until the 1980s, many library catalogs used 3x5 inch cards in file drawers to display a book's title, author, subject matter, and an abbreviated alpha-numeric string (call number) which indicated the physical location of the book within the library's shelves.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The Dewey Decimal System employed by libraries for the classification of library materials by subject is an early example of metadata usage.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The early paper catalog had information regarding whichever item was described on said card: title, author, subject, and a number as to where to find said item.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Beginning in the 1980s and 1990s, many libraries replaced these paper file cards with computer databases.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] These computer databases make it much easier and faster for users to do keyword searches.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Another form of older metadata collection is the use by the US Census Bureau of what is known as the "Long Form".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The Long Form asks questions that are used to create demographic data to find patterns of distribution.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Libraries employ metadata in library catalogues, most commonly as part of an Integrated Library Management System.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata is obtained by cataloging resources such as books, periodicals, DVDs, web pages or digital images.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This data is stored in the integrated library management system, ILMS, using the MARC metadata standard.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The purpose is to direct patrons to the physical or electronic location of items or areas they seek as well as to provide a description of the item/s in question.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] More recent and specialized instances of library metadata include the establishment of digital libraries including e-print repositories and digital image libraries.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] While often based on library principles, the focus on non-librarian use, especially in providing metadata, means they do not follow traditional or common cataloging approaches.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Given the custom nature of included materials, metadata fields are often specially created e.g. taxonomic classification fields, location fields, keywords, or copyright statement.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Standard file information such as file size and format are usually automatically included.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Library operation has for decades been a key topic in efforts toward international standardization.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Standards for metadata in digital libraries include Dublin Core, METS, MODS, DDI, DOI, URN, PREMIS schema, EML, and OAI-PMH.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Leading libraries in the world give hints on their metadata standards strategies.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] A similar concept is the synset, short for *synonym set*, a group of one or more synonyms that share a common meaning in some context.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Synsets are a fundamental concept in computational linguistics and lexical semantics, most notably used in the WordNet lexical database of English.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The concept has been extended to other languages and multilingual projects such as EuroWordNet, BabelNet, and the Global WordNet initiative.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata for scientific publications is often created by journal publishers and citation databases such as PubMed and Web of Science.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The data contained within manuscripts or accompanying them as supplementary material is less often subject to metadata creation, though they may be submitted to e.g. biomedical databases after publication.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The original authors and database curators then become responsible for metadata creation, with the assistance of automated processes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Comprehensive metadata for all experimental data is the foundation of the FAIR Guiding Principles, or the standards for ensuring research data are findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Such metadata can then be utilized, complemented, and made accessible in useful ways.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] OpenAlex is a free online index of over 200 million scientific documents that integrates and provides metadata such as sources, citations, author information, scientific fields, and research topics.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Its API and open source website can be used for metascience, scientometrics, and novel tools that query this semantic web of papers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Another project under development, Scholia, uses the metadata of scientific publications for various visualizations and aggregation features such as providing a simple user interface summarizing literature about a specific feature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus using Wikidata's "main subject" property.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In research labor, transparent metadata about authors' contributions to works have been proposed – e.g. the role played in the production of the paper, the level of contribution and the responsibilities.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Moreover, various metadata about scientific outputs can be created or complemented – for instance, some organizations attempt to track and link citations of papers as 'Supporting', 'Mentioning' or 'Contrasting' the study.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata in a museum context is the information that trained cultural documentation specialists, such as archivists, librarians, museum registrars and curators, create to index, structure, describe, identify, or otherwise specify works of art, architecture, cultural objects and their images.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Descriptive metadata is most commonly used in museum contexts for object identification and resource recovery purposes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Many museums and cultural heritage centers recognize that given the diversity of artworks and cultural objects, no single model or standard suffices to describe and catalog cultural works.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] For example, a sculpted Indigenous artifact could be classified as an artwork, an archaeological artifact, or an Indigenous heritage item.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] These standards use HTML and XML markup languages for machine processing, publication and implementation.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules (AACR), originally developed for characterizing books, have also been applied to cultural objects, works of art and architecture.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Standards, such as the CCO, are integrated within a Museum's Collections Management System (CMS), a database through which museums are able to manage their collections, acquisitions, loans and conservation.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Scholars and professionals in the field note that the "quickly evolving landscape of standards and technologies" creates challenges for cultural documentarians, specifically non-technically trained professionals.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Most collecting institutions and museums use a relational database to categorize cultural works and their images.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Relational databases and metadata work to document and describe the complex relationships amongst cultural objects and multi-faceted works of art, as well as between objects and places, people, and artistic movements.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Relational database structures are also beneficial within collecting institutions and museums because they allow for archivists to make a clear distinction between cultural objects and their images; an unclear distinction could lead to confusing and inaccurate searches.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The established institutional cataloging practices, goals, and expertise of cultural documentarians and database structure also influence the information ascribed to cultural objects and the ways in which cultural objects are categorized.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Additionally, museums often employ standardized commercial collection management software that prescribes and limits the ways in which archivists can describe artworks and cultural objects.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] As well, collecting institutions and museums use Controlled Vocabularies to describe cultural objects and artworks in their collections.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Getty Vocabularies and the Library of Congress Controlled Vocabularies are reputable within the museum community and are recommended by CCO standards.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Museums are encouraged to use controlled vocabularies that are contextual and relevant to their collections and enhance the functionality of their digital information systems.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Controlled Vocabularies are beneficial within databases because they provide a high level of consistency, improving resource retrieval.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata structures, including controlled vocabularies, reflect the ontologies of the systems from which they were created.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Often the processes through which cultural objects are described and categorized through metadata in museums do not reflect the perspectives of the maker communities.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata has been instrumental in the creation of digital information systems and archives within museums and has made it easier for museums to publish digital content online.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This has enabled audiences who might not have had access to cultural objects due to geographic or economic barriers to have access to them.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In the 2000s, as more museums have adopted archival standards and created intricate databases, discussions about Linked Data between museum databases have come up in the museum, archival, and library science communities.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Collection Management Systems (CMS) and Digital Asset Management tools can be local or shared systems.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Digital Humanities scholars note many benefits of interoperability between museum databases and collections, while also acknowledging the difficulties of achieving such interoperability.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Problems involving metadata in litigation in the United States are becoming widespread.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Courts have looked at various questions involving metadata, including the discoverability of metadata by parties.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The Federal Rules of Civil Procedure have specific rules for discovery of electronically stored information, and subsequent case law applying those rules has elucidated on the litigant's duty to produce metadata when litigating in federal court.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In October 2009, the Arizona Supreme Court has ruled that metadata records are public record.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Document metadata have proven particularly important in legal environments in which litigation has requested metadata, that can include sensitive information detrimental to a certain party in court.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Using metadata removal tools to "clean" or redact documents can mitigate the risks of unwittingly sending sensitive data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This process partially (see data remanence) protects law firms from potentially damaging leaking of sensitive data through electronic discovery.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Opinion polls have shown that 45% of Americans are "not at all confident" in the ability of social media sites to ensure their personal data is secure and 40% say that social media sites should not be able to store any information on individuals.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] 76% of Americans say that they are not confident that the information advertising agencies collect on them is secure and 50% say that online advertising agencies should not be allowed to record any of their information at all.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In the EU, the Snowden disclosures have been influential in its review of matters concerning privacy and the processing of personal data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] As of 2025, of the 18 European countries surveyed by the Data Retention Directive, only Germany, the Netherlands and Romania do not have any data retention rules in force.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] On 6 October 2020, the Court of Justice for the European Union (CJEU) ruled that indiscriminate mass data retention schemes are illegal under EU law.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] With France passing a law on 18 December 2013 that facilitates the collection of data by the French military and intelligence services.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] While in April 2022 the Portuguese Constitutional Court declared unconstitutional the CJEU laws on the retention of data generated or processed in connection with the provision of publicly available electronic communications services or of public communications networks.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In Australia, the need to strengthen national security has resulted in the introduction of a new metadata storage law.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This new law means that both security and policing agencies will be allowed to access up to 2 years of an individual's metadata, with the aim of making it easier to stop any terrorist attacks and serious crimes from happening.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Legislative metadata has been discussed in various forums, such as workshops held by the Legal Information Institute at the Cornell Law School on 22 and 23 March 2010.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The documentation for these workshops is titled "Suggested metadata practices for legislation and regulations".
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Australian medical research pioneered the definition of metadata for applications in health care.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] That approach offers the first recognized attempt to adhere to international standards in medical sciences instead of defining a proprietary standard under the World Health Organization (WHO) umbrella.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The medical community yet did not approve of the need to follow metadata standards despite research that supported these standards.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Research studies in the fields of biomedicine and molecular biology frequently yield large quantities of data, including results of genome or meta-genome sequencing, proteomics data, and even notes or plans created during the course of research itself.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Each data type involves its own variety of metadata and the processes necessary to produce these metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] General metadata standards, such as ISA-Tab, allow researchers to create and exchange experimental metadata in consistent formats.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Specific experimental approaches frequently have their own metadata standards and systems: metadata standards for mass spectrometry include mzML and SPLASH, while XML-based standards such as PDBML and SRA XML serve as standards for macromolecular structure and sequencing data, respectively.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The products of biomedical research are generally realized as peer-reviewed manuscripts and these publications are yet another source of data .
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] A data warehouse (DW) is a repository of an organization's electronically stored data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Data warehouses are designed to manage and store the data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Data warehouses differ from business intelligence (BI) systems because BI systems are designed to use data to create reports and analyze the information, to provide strategic guidance to management.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata is an important tool in how data is stored in data warehouses.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The purpose of a data warehouse is to house standardized, structured, consistent, integrated, correct, "cleaned" and timely data, extracted from various operational systems in an organization.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The extracted data are integrated in the data warehouse environment to provide an enterprise-wide perspective.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Data are structured in a way to serve the reporting and analytic requirements.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The design of structural metadata commonality using a data modeling method such as entity-relationship model diagramming is important in any data warehouse development effort.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] They detail metadata on each piece of data in the data warehouse.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] An essential component of a data warehouse/business intelligence system is the metadata and tools to manage and retrieve the metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Ralph Kimball describes metadata as the DNA of the data warehouse as metadata defines the elements of the data warehouse and how they work together.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Kimball et al. refer to three main categories of metadata: technical, business and process.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Technical metadata is primarily definitional, while business metadata and process metadata are primarily descriptive.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The HTML format used to define web pages allows for the inclusion of a variety of types of metadata, from basic descriptive text, dates and keywords to further advanced metadata schemes such as the Dublin Core, e-GMS, and AGLS standards.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Pages and files can also be geotagged with coordinates, categorized or tagged, including collaboratively such as with folksonomies.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] When media has identifiers set or when such can be generated, information such as file tags and descriptions can be pulled or scraped from the Internet – for example about movies.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Various online databases are aggregated and provide metadata for various data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The collaboratively built Wikidata has identifiers not just for media but also abstract concepts, various objects, and other entities, that can be looked up by humans and machines to retrieve useful information and to link knowledge in other knowledge bases and databases.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata may be included in the page's header or in a separate file.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Microformats allow metadata to be added to on-page data in a way that regular web users do not see, but computers, web crawlers and search engines can readily access.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Many search engines are cautious about using metadata in their ranking algorithms because of exploitation of metadata and the practice of search engine optimization, SEO, to improve rankings.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] See the Meta element article for further discussion.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This cautious attitude may be justified as people, according to Doctorow, are not executing care and diligence when creating their own metadata and that metadata is part of a competitive environment where the metadata is used to promote the metadata creators own purposes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Studies show that search engines respond to web pages with metadata implementations, and Google has an announcement on its site showing the meta tags that its search engine understands.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Enterprise search startup Swiftype recognizes metadata as a relevance signal that webmasters can implement for their website-specific search engine, even releasing their own extension, known as Meta Tags 2.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This metadata can be linked to the video media thanks to the video servers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Most major broadcast sporting events like FIFA World Cup or the Olympic Games use this metadata to distribute their video content to TV stations through keywords.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] It is often the host broadcaster who is in charge of organizing metadata through its *International Broadcast Centre* and its video servers.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This metadata is recorded with the images and entered by metadata operators (*loggers*) who associate in live metadata available in *metadata grids* through software (such as Multicam(LSM) or IPDirector used during the FIFA World Cup or Olympic Games).
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Ecological and environmental metadata is intended to document the "who, what, when, where, why, and how" of data collection for a particular study.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] This typically means which organization or institution collected the data, what type of data, which date(s) the data was collected, the rationale for the data collection, and the methodology used for the data collection.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata should be generated in a format commonly used by the most relevant science community, such as Darwin Core, Ecological Metadata Language, or Dublin Core.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata editing tools exist to facilitate metadata generation (e.g.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata should describe the provenance of the data (where they originated, as well as any transformations the data underwent) and how to give credit for (cite) the data products.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] When first released in 1982, Compact Discs only contained a Table Of Contents (TOC) with the number of tracks on the disc and their length in samples.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Fourteen years later in 1996, a revision of the CD Red Book standard added CD-Text to carry additional metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Shortly thereafter, it became common for personal computers to retrieve metadata from external sources (e.g.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Digital audio formats such as digital audio files superseded music formats such as cassette tapes and CDs in the 2000s.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Digital audio files could be labeled with more information than could be contained in just the file name.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] That descriptive information is called the **audio tag** or audio metadata in general.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Computer programs specializing in adding or modifying this information are called tag editors.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata can be used to name, describe, catalog, and indicate ownership or copyright for a digital audio file, and its presence makes it much easier to locate a specific audio file within a group, typically through use of a search engine that accesses the metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] As different digital audio formats were developed, attempts were made to standardize a specific location within the digital files where this information could be stored.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] As a result, almost all digital audio formats, including mp3, broadcast wav, and AIFF files, have similar standardized locations that can be populated with metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The metadata for compressed and uncompressed digital music is often encoded in the ID3 tag.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Common editors such as TagLib support MP3, Ogg Vorbis, FLAC, MPC, Speex, WavPack TrueAudio, WAV, AIFF, MP4, and ASF file formats.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] With the availability of cloud applications, which include those to add metadata to content, metadata is increasingly available over the Internet.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored either *internally*, in the same file or structure as the data (this is also called *embedded metadata*), or *externally*, in a separate file or field from the described data.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] A data repository typically stores the metadata *detached* from the data but can be designed to support embedded metadata approaches.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored in either human-readable or binary form.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Storing metadata in a human-readable format such as XML can be useful because users can understand and edit it without specialized tools.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] However, text-based formats are rarely optimized for storage capacity, communication time, or processing speed.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] A binary metadata format enables efficiency in all these respects, but requires special software to convert the binary information into human-readable content.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Each relational database system has its own mechanisms for storing metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In database terminology, this set of metadata is referred to as the catalog.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the information schema, but not all databases implement it, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] For an example of database-specific metadata access methods, see Oracle metadata.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Programmatic access to metadata is possible using APIs such as JDBC, or SchemaCrawler.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] One of the first satirical examinations of the concept of Metadata as we understand it today is American science fiction author Hal Draper's short story, "MS Fnd in a Lbry" (1961).
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Here, the knowledge of all Mankind is condensed into an object the size of a desk drawer, however, the magnitude of the metadata (e.g. catalog of catalogs of... , as well as indexes and histories) eventually leads to dire yet humorous consequences for the human race.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] The story prefigures the modern consequences of allowing metadata to become more important than the real data it is concerned with, and the risks inherent in that eventuality as a cautionary tale.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Documentation refers to all contextual information that explains and describes a dataset, system, or research process to ensure it is understandable, usable, and reusable.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] It covers broad details such as the study background, data collection methods, file inventories, codebooks, data dictionaries, user guides, and workflow notes.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] In contrast, metadata is a specific and highly structured form of documentation that provides standardized information about the data itself—such as the title, creator, file format, size, access conditions, and how files or sections are organized.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Metadata and documentation are therefore related but distinct concepts in information management.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] Both play crucial roles in data governance, usability, and preservation.
[src:open-graph-protocol/metadata-p02] While documentation gives the full narrative and instructions surrounding the data, metadata offers concise, structured descriptors that help users and systems identify, locate, manage and preserve the data efficiently.
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] The **Open Graph Protocol** is a specialized web page protocol used between client devices (computers, mobile phones, tablets, etc.).
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] The protocol was initially designed for Facebook to enable developers to integrate their pages into Facebook's global mapping/tracking tool Social Graph.
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] In recent years the protocol gained wide spread use and also was integrated into functionality in major messaging apps.
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] The protocol utilized in messaging apps such as iMessage adds the functionality whereby if a user shares a URL, the corresponding Open Graph metadata of the URL will allow for the display of the thumbnail or assigned image as part of the link.
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] The protocol was initially published in 2010 as part of Facebook.
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] Starting in 2016 it became integrated with iMessage in a functionality Apple initially called Rich Link.
[src:open-graph-protocol/open-graph-protocol] Later on it was also integrated with Whatsapp messaging.
